{"cursor":"29855","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Quantum tunnelling' (also spelled 'quantum tunneling' in American English)\nrefers to the quantum mechanical phenomenon where a particle tunnels through a\nbarrier that it classically could not surmount. This plays an essential role in\nseveral physical phenomena, such as the nuclear fusion that occurs in main\nsequence stars like the sun, College Physics Vol. 2 Serway and Vuille\nand has important applications to modern devices such as the tunnel\ndiode Taylor, J: Modern Physics, page 234. Prentice Hall, 2004. and\nthe scanning tunneling microscope. The effect was predicted in the early 20th\ncentury and its acceptance, as a general physical phenomenon, came mid-\ncentury. Mohsen Razavy, \"Quantum Theory of Tunneling\", pages\n4, 462. World Scientific Publishing Co. 2003\n\nTunnelling is often explained using the Heisenberg uncertainty principle and the\nwaveâparticle duality of matter. Purely quantum mechanical concepts are central\nto the phenomenon, so quantum tunnelling is one of the novel implications of\nquantum mechanics.\n","linknr":577,"url":"Quantum_tunneling","recorded":1362512647,"links":62,"instances":["physics","physics"],"pdf":["http://cosmos.asu.edu/publications/papers/'Quantum%20Tunelling%20Time'%20AJP000023.pdf","http://cosmos.asu.edu/publications/papers/'Quantum%20Tunelling%20Time'%20AJP000023.pdf"],"categories":["Particle physics","Quantum mechanics","Solid state engineering"],"headings":["History","Introduction to the concept","Related phenomena","Applications","Faster than light","Mathematical discussions of quantum tunnelling","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/Qm_template_pic_4.svg/210px-Qm_template_pic_4.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/TunnelEffektKling1.png/300px-TunnelEffek